File: The children of separated parents will now be allowed to move between homes during the lockdown period. JOHANNESBURG - There has been a breakthrough for frustrated co-parents during the 21-day lockdown. The children of separated parents will now be allowed to move between homes during the lockdown period. Government has caved into public outcry and the threat of legal challenges by amending Disaster Management regulations. WATCH: Comply with lockdown regulations, Mkhize urges The amendment to the regulations was published by Social Development Minister Lindiwe Zulu in the Government Gazette on Tuesday. According to the amendment, the parent or caregiver transporting the child will have to be in possession of a court order or parenting agreement. Children are not allowed to be moved to a home where a person is known to have come into contact with a COVID-19 patient. READ: Ramaphosa still undecided on lockdown extension Responding to the earlier public outcry, Zulu had said parents had to stick it out during the lockdown period, to avoid the spread of the coronavirus. Parents threatened to take the government to court if the regulations were not amended. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs